      "message": "● Here is the security review.\n\n  ---\n  Security Review: Oauth2ProxyTokenRealm implementation\n\n  Critical\n\n  1. getCredentials() returns the username — contract violation with a test-implementation mismatch\n\n  Oauth2ProxyToken.getCredentials() returns user (the username string). The Javadoc says \"Contains no credential\", and Oauth2ProxyTokenRealmTest asserts\n  assertNull(authenticationInfo.getCredentials()) — but the test must be failing because the realm stores token.getCredentials() (the username) inside\n  SimpleAuthenticationInfo. The result: credentials equal the username, which can appear in Shiro audit logs and is semantically wrong.\n\n  Fix:\n  // Oauth2ProxyToken\n  @Override\n  public Object getCredentials() {\n      return null;  // trust is in the proxy, not in a credential value\n  }\n  // Oauth2ProxyTokenRealm constructor\n  public Oauth2ProxyTokenRealm() {\n      super();\n      setAuthenticationTokenClass(Oauth2ProxyToken.class);\n      setCredentialsMatcher(new AllowAllCredentialsMatcher());\n  }\n\n  ---\n  2. Enumeration\u003cString\u003e is single-use — groups silently disappear on any second read\n\n  Enumeration has no reset(). Once parseRoles() exhausts it via asIterator().forEachRemaining(...), the enumeration is empty. If Shiro touches the token again\n  (multi-realm scenario, retry, cache miss), parseRoles() returns Set.of() and the user is authenticated with no roles. This is a correctness and security issue: wrong\n  authorisation rather than an outright error.\n\n  Fix — materialise into a List at token creation time:\n  // Oauth2ProxyTokenFilter.createToken\n  return new Oauth2ProxyToken(Collections.list(httpRequest.getHeaders(PROXY_HEADER_GROUPS)), user);\n  // Oauth2ProxyToken\n  public record Oauth2ProxyToken(List\u003cString\u003e groups, String user) implements AuthenticationToken { … }\n\n  ---\n  High\n\n  3. No blank check on the forwarded username\n\n  onAccessDenied rejects a null X-Forwarded-User header but accepts an empty string (\" \"). Some proxies forward a blank header on misconfiguration. With the current\n  code an empty string becomes the authenticated principal, which is a security hole: any request with X-Forwarded-User:  gains a valid (if useless-looking) Shiro\n  subject.\n\n  Fix in doGetAuthenticationInfo:\n  final var user \u003d proxyToken.user();\n  if (user \u003d\u003d null || user.isBlank()) {\n      throw new AuthenticationException(\"X-Forwarded-User is absent or blank\");\n  }\n\n  ---\n  4. Role namespace stripping can collapse unrelated IdP roles into the same ODL role\n\n  parseRoles takes only p[p.length - 1] after splitting on :. This means audit:admin, netconf:admin, and syslog:admin all become admin. An IdP that issues a narrow,\n  application-scoped role like monitoring:admin inadvertently grants full ODL admin. This is a privilege-escalation path that is invisible in the IdP configuration.\n\n  The least-surprise fix is to take the full role string rather than stripping the namespace:\n  .map(p -\u003e p.trim())   // no namespace stripping\n  If stripping is intentional for a specific naming convention, it should be narrowly scoped (e.g., strip only a single configured prefix) and documented explicitly\n  with the rationale.\n\n  ---\n  Medium\n\n  5. Inconsistent HttpServletRequest access in onAccessDenied\n\n  createToken correctly uses WebUtils.toHttp(request), but onAccessDenied uses a raw cast ((HttpServletRequest) request). The raw cast bypasses Shiro\u0027s validation\n  wrapper and gives a misleading ClassCastException instead of a meaningful error when called outside an HTTP context.\n\n  // line 41 — replace\n  final var token \u003d ((HttpServletRequest) request).getHeader(PROXY_HEADER_USER);\n  // with\n  final var token \u003d WebUtils.toHttp(request).getHeader(PROXY_HEADER_USER);\n\n  ---\n  Low / Informational\n\n  6. Comment references the wrong header name\n\n  parseRoles() carries the comment \"Parse roles from X-Auth-Request-Groups header\" but the constant is X-Forwarded-Groups. X-Auth-Request-Groups is the OAuth2 Proxy\n  header variant used when ODL is the application (not an upstream), so this is a factually wrong comment that will mislead operators configuring their proxy.\n\n  7. Collectors.toSet() followed by addAll creates an unnecessary intermediate copy\n\n  Minor style: replace out.addAll(stream.collect(Collectors.toSet())) with stream.forEach(out::add).",
